const faqs = [
  { q: "What is GE Café's customizable hardware program?", a: "GE Café's signature differentiator in the wall oven market is the customizable handle + knob hardware program. Customers can swap the factory-installed handle and knob hardware for coordinated designer-finish options (brushed stainless, brushed bronze, brushed copper, matte black, and other hardware colors) to match the kitchen's metal accents. The hardware swaps are user-serviceable — designed for the customer to change hardware themselves or with minor technician assistance rather than requiring factory service. For LA customers, this means a kitchen can be specified in Café Matte White with brushed-copper hardware for a coordinated look against copper-finish cabinet pulls; if the kitchen remodels later and switches to brushed-bronze cabinet pulls, the Café hardware can swap to brushed-bronze without replacing the appliance. Service side: hardware swaps don't typically require our involvement; interior mechanical service runs at standard Café service economics." },
  { q: "Café vs Profile vs Monogram — which GE tier should I spec?", a: "Three distinct premium tiers within GE Appliances, each positioned for different buyer priorities. <b>GE Café</b> (this page) — style-first premium $2.5-8k tier, Matte Black/White finishes + customizable hardware, positions against Samsung Bespoke + LG STUDIO at aesthetic-driven buying. <b>GE Profile</b> — feature-focused premium $1.5-5k tier, True European Convection + SmartHQ + Air Fry, positions against Samsung + LG at feature-driven buying. <b>GE Monogram</b> — ultra-luxury $5-25k tier with Statement Collection + Advantium tri-tech, positions against Wolf/Miele/Sub-Zero Group at luxury-driven buying. For LA renovation work: Café appeals to design-forward buyers who want the appliance to coordinate with kitchen aesthetic; Profile appeals to pragmatic premium buyers who want features; Monogram appeals to luxury buyers. All three route parts through the same Haier-owned GE Appliances distribution in Louisville Kentucky." },
  { q: "Does GE Café have True European Convection or just basic convection?", a: "Current GE Café wall oven generations include True European Convection (third-element convection system) — the same technology implemented in GE Profile at the premium tier. Café distinguishes from Profile primarily at aesthetic rather than feature-technology level. Both use third-element convection for more even multi-rack cooking, both support SmartHQ Wi-Fi integration, both offer Air Fry mode on current generations. The Café differentiation is finish quality (premium Matte Black/White panel processes), hardware customization (knob + handle swap program), and handle design (more substantial premium-feel hardware). For service, Café wall oven failure modes and diagnostic patterns largely mirror Profile — same Haier GE Appliances parts infrastructure, similar control platforms." },
  { q: "Does service work affect the customizable hardware?", a: "Generally no. Interior mechanical service (bake element, convection fan, control board, sensor work, door hinge service) doesn't touch the exterior Matte Black/White panel or the customizable handle + knob hardware. Our cabinet-preservation approach during any partial-pull service protects the panel finish from scratches or marring. The customizable hardware stays installed and isn't disturbed during typical service calls. If exterior panel damage occurs — dented or scratched Matte panel, damaged hardware — those are separate service domains with different parts-chain considerations: panel replacement quoted individually through Haier GE Appliances specialty-parts channel; hardware swaps are customer-handled from GE's hardware-customization program." },
  { q: "What does GE Café wall oven repair cost in LA?", a: "Residential diagnostic is $89, waived when you authorize the repair. GE Café wall oven service at style-first premium pricing (slightly above Profile reflecting Café's premium finishes): bake element $300-$480; True European Convection third-element $340-$540; convection fan motor $380-$600; control board $460-$780; temperature sensor $240-$380; door hinge $280-$460; door glass $400-$660; thermostat $320-$500; SmartHQ firmware + connectivity reset $180-$320; self-clean door-lock motor $240-$400; self-clean thermal sensor $240-$380; double wall oven per-cavity service $400-$700. Haier Louisville distribution typical 2-4 days common Café parts, 3-5 days Café-specialty components. Matte panel replacement quoted individually reflecting finish-specialty supply." }
];

